        <h2>Use of Resources</h2>
        <h3>The rise of railroads in the 1920's</h3>
        <p>Text Excerpts: <i>“I went up to New York with Tom on the train one afternoon, and when we stopped by the ashheaps he jumped to his feet and, taking hold of my elbow, literally forced me from the car.”</i> -Nick Carraway</p>
        <p>Explanation of relation to history: After World War I, improvements were made to living conditions in the United States, including improvements in transportation. Railroads were expanded upon its previous coverage in the the states by increasing them immensely. The train in New York that Tom and Nick rode on most likely was one of these new additions to the railways of the United States.</p>
        <p>Additional Research on topic: Railroads were at its all-time high in 1916, as the United States had 250,000 miles of tracks built. The “Roaring 20’s” was a pinnacle period for the construction of the railroad system. Pullman cars were introduced for comfortable long-distance travelling.</p>
        <p>Source Citation:</br> "Transportation improvements in the 1920s | NCpedia." 2010. 20 Feb. 2015 &lt;http://ncpedia.org/transportation/overview-1920s&gt;</p>
